DDL commands create, modify, and delete database structures. These commands are auto-committed in most databases.

CREATE TABLE:
Syntax: CREATE TABLE table_name (column_name datatype constraint, ...);
Constraints:
• PRIMARY KEY: Ensures uniqueness and non-null values
• UNIQUE: Ensures all values in column are unique
• NOT NULL: Column must have a value
• DEFAULT: Sets default value if none provided
• FOREIGN KEY: References primary key in another table
• CHECK: Validates data based on condition

Example:
CREATE TABLE employees (
  emp_id INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
  name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
  salary DECIMAL(10, 2) CHECK (salary > 0),
  dept_id INT FOREIGN KEY REFERENCES departments(dept_id)
);

ALTER TABLE:
• ADD COLUMN: ALTER TABLE table_name ADD COLUMN new_col datatype;
• DROP COLUMN: ALTER TABLE table_name DROP COLUMN col_name;
• MODIFY COLUMN: ALTER TABLE table_name MODIFY COLUMN col_name new_datatype;
• ADD CONSTRAINT: ALTER TABLE table_name ADD PRIMARY KEY (col_name);
• DROP CONSTRAINT: ALTER TABLE table_name DROP CONSTRAINT constraint_name;

DROP TABLE:
Syntax: DROP TABLE table_name;
Removes entire table structure and data. Cannot be rolled back.

TRUNCATE TABLE:
Syntax: TRUNCATE TABLE table_name;
Deletes all rows but keeps structure. Faster than DELETE.

CREATE INDEX:
Syntax: CREATE INDEX idx_name ON table_name (column);
Improves query performance. Can be UNIQUE. DROP INDEX idx_name;

DML commands modify data within tables. Changes can be rolled back using transactions.

INSERT:
Syntax: INSERT INTO table_name (col1, col2) VALUES (val1, val2);
Variations:
• Single row: INSERT INTO table_name VALUES (val1, val2, ...);
• Multiple rows: INSERT INTO table_name (col1, col2) VALUES (val1, val2), (val3, val4);
• From SELECT: INSERT INTO table_name SELECT * FROM another_table WHERE condition;

UPDATE:
Syntax: UPDATE table_name SET col1 = val1, col2 = val2 WHERE condition;
Always use WHERE clause; without it, ALL rows are updated.
Example: UPDATE employees SET salary = salary * 1.1 WHERE dept_id = 5;

DELETE:
Syntax: DELETE FROM table_name WHERE condition;
WHERE is optional but recommended; without it, all records are deleted.
Example: DELETE FROM employees WHERE emp_id = 10;

Difference between DELETE, TRUNCATE, DROP:
• DELETE: Removes rows, can be rolled back, triggers fire
• TRUNCATE: Removes all rows, faster, resets identity
• DROP: Removes entire table structure, cannot rollback

Transactions (ACID):
BEGIN TRANSACTION; or START TRANSACTION;
COMMIT; (finalize changes)
ROLLBACK; (undo changes)

Example:
BEGIN TRANSACTION;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE acc_id = 1;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 100 WHERE acc_id = 2;
COMMIT;

Joins combine rows from two or more tables based on related columns.

INNER JOIN:
Syntax: SELECT * FROM table1 INNER JOIN table2 ON table1.id = table2.id;
Returns only matching rows from both tables. Most commonly used join.

LEFT JOIN (LEFT OUTER JOIN):
Syntax: SELECT * FROM table1 LEFT JOIN table2 ON table1.id = table2.id;
Returns all rows from left table and matching rows from right. Non-matches show NULL.

RIGHT JOIN (RIGHT OUTER JOIN):
Syntax: SELECT * FROM table1 RIGHT JOIN table2 ON table1.id = table2.id;
Returns all rows from right table and matching rows from left. Non-matches show NULL.

FULL OUTER JOIN:
Syntax: SELECT * FROM table1 FULL OUTER JOIN table2 ON table1.id = table2.id;
Returns all rows from both tables. Non-matching rows show NULL. Not in MySQL (use UNION).

CROSS JOIN:
Syntax: SELECT * FROM table1 CROSS JOIN table2;
Cartesian product: every row of table1 with every row of table2. Result size = rows(t1) × rows(t2)

SELF JOIN:
Syntax: SELECT a.name, b.name FROM employees a JOIN employees b ON a.manager_id = b.emp_id;
Joins table with itself. Requires aliases. Example: Find employees and their managers.

NATURAL JOIN:
Syntax: SELECT * FROM table1 NATURAL JOIN table2;
Automatically joins on columns with same name. Use explicit joins instead.

Multiple Joins:
SELECT * FROM t1 JOIN t2 ON t1.id = t2.id JOIN t3 ON t2.id = t3.id;
Chain multiple joins. Order matters for performance.

Subqueries (nested queries) allow queries within queries. Views provide stored queries for reusability.

Subqueries (Inline):
Syntax: SELECT * FROM table WHERE column IN (SELECT column FROM another_table WHERE condition);
Inner query executes first, result used by outer query. Can return single value, row, or multiple rows.

Types of Subqueries:
1. Scalar: Returns single value
   SELECT * FROM employees WHERE salary > (SELECT AVG(salary) FROM employees);

2. Row: Returns single row with multiple columns
   SELECT * FROM employees WHERE (dept_id, salary) = (SELECT dept_id, MAX(salary) FROM employees);

3. Table: Returns multiple rows and columns
   SELECT * FROM employees WHERE dept_id IN (SELECT dept_id FROM departments WHERE location = 'NYC');

Correlated Subquery:
References columns from outer query. Executes once per outer query row (slower).
SELECT name FROM employees e WHERE salary > (SELECT AVG(salary) FROM employees WHERE dept_id = e.dept_id);

Subquery in FROM (Derived Table):
Syntax: SELECT * FROM (SELECT col1, col2 FROM table WHERE condition) AS derived_table;
Creates temporary table from subquery. Must have alias.

EXISTS Operator:
Syntax: SELECT * FROM employees WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM orders WHERE orders.emp_id = employees.emp_id);
Checks if subquery returns any rows. More efficient than IN for large datasets.

Views (Stored Queries):
Syntax: CREATE VIEW view_name AS SELECT columns FROM table WHERE condition;
Virtual table based on query result. Simplifies complex queries. Data security.

Using Views:
SELECT * FROM view_name;

Altering & Dropping Views:
ALTER VIEW view_name AS SELECT ... ;
DROP VIEW view_name;

Advantages:
• Simplify complex queries
• Security (hide underlying schema)
• Consistency (same logic everywhere)
• Maintenance (update once, used everywhere)
